unt":0,"incoming_link_count":6,"reads":340,"readers_count":339,"score":113.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":467993,"topic_slug":"how-do-you-program-pid","display_username":"Kanaan Kratzer","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.com/RegisJesuitRobotics/Competition2024","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"GitHub - RegisJesuitRobotics/Competition2024: Robot code for FIRST Robotics Competition 2024 CRESCENDO","clicks":51}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":57510,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/how-do-you-program-pid/467993/3","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3402050,"name":"","username":"LPryor","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/lpryor/{size}/220287_2.png","created_at":"2024-06-26T02:17:59.681Z","cooked":"<p>This was a big teaching point for me and my team this year.  There are a number of excellent resources out there.  The WPILIB link above has some great tools for learning how to tune things. I can’t recommend them enough.</p>
<p>One thing that’s been useful is this youtube link - I don’t know where I originally found it - but I find it does a great job of explaining things without any worlds whatsoever<br>
<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qKy98Cbcltw" rel="noopener nofollow ugc"><span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> demo (youtube.com)</a></p>
<p>It take a little practice to get the hang of, and there’s a bit of art to it. We tend to looks at the values this way.  The goal is to get a motor to reach a particular setpoint (or speed). Generally we tend to zero all the values and approach things in this order.</p>
<ul>
<li>P(Proportional value) - Manipulate this one first. You want the motor to reach it’s setpoint and oscillate a bit. You can then back off of P.</li>
<li>I - Integral - This is error correction. If your motor isn’t quite reaching it’s setpoint add I</li>
<li>D- Derivative - This provides dampening to prevent you from overshooting. This will slow down the motor as it approaches it’s setpoint.</li>
</ul>
<p>Note 0 - The WPILIB link above and it’s javascript tutorials are FANTASTIC. These really helped us.</p>
<p>Note 1 - There is often more than one solution to this problem. It’s really about finding something that works for you.</p>
<p>Note 2- With your robot its possible to use the REV client and Phoenix Tuner to pinpoint these values quickly.</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2024-06-26T02:17:59.681Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":15,"reads":329,"readers_count":328,"score":200.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":467993,"topic_slug":"how-do-you-program-pid","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qKy98Cbcltw","internal":false,"reflection":false,"clicks":47}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":4}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":55309,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Mentor 8280, President Motor City Alliance"},"post_url":"/t/how-do-you-program-pid/467993/4","custom_user_title":"Mentor 8280, President Motor City Alliance","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":4}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":4,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3402395,"name":"SLAB-Mr.Thomas","username":"SLAB-Mr.Thomas","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/slab-mr.thomas/{size}/182153_2.png","created_at":"2024-06-26T16:30:53.551Z","cooked":"<p>I’m not sure if you wanted to understand and program your own <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> controller or if you wanted to know how to use preprogrammed controllers say from WPILib, Rev, or <span class="abbreviation">CTRE<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Cross The Road Electronics"></template></span>.</p>
<p>For the math details I suggest also looking at the source code for the WPILib <code>PIDController</code>.</p>
<p>To use the controllers look at others’ code as suggested and you can take a look at my command-based examples in <a href="https://github.com/tom131313/Example-LED" class="inline-onebox" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">GitHub - tom131313/Example-LED</a> specifically <code>RobotContainer</code> has a Xbox trigger axis binding for the <code>AchieveHueGoal</code> WPILib PIDController.</p>
<p>You can run the example project in simulation mode and see the fake LED output which for the <code>AchieveHueGoal</code> example shows the progress of going around the color wheel from 0 to the desired setpoint from the Xbox. Play with <code>kP</code> to see how you converge to the setpoint.</p>
<p>Oblarg posted this code here on <span class="abbreviation">CD<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Chief Delphi"></template></span> that I use as a model to use WPILib PIDController:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">Example of two ways to create a PID controller Command as factory in a subsystem
(Don't use the WPILib PIDControllerCommand; create your own with a factory)
// in subsystem scope
// we need a motor and sensor for feedback
private final MotorController motor = new FooMotor();
private final Encoder encoder = new Encoder(...);
// Example 1 we could have a PIDController as a field in the subsystem itself...
private final PIDController controller = new PIDController(...);
// this command captures the subsystem's PIDController, like PIDSubsystem
public Command moveToPosition(double position) {
return runOnce(controller::reset)
.andThen(run(() -&gt; {
motor.set(controller.calculate(
encoder.getPosition(),
position
));
}).finallyDo(motor::stop);
}
// Example 2 if we don't want to persist the controller in the subsystem after the command ends...
// this command captures its *own* controller, like PIDCommand
public Command moveToPosition(double position) {
PIDController controller = new PIDController(...);
// we don't have to reset a fresh controller
return run(() -&gt; {
motor.set(controller.calculate(
encoder.getPosition(),
position
));
}).finallyDo(motor::stop);
}
</code></pre>","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2024-06-26T16:39:05.064Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":8,"reads":255,"readers_count":254,"score":91.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":467993,"topic_slug":"how-do-you-program-pid","display_username":"SLAB-Mr.Thomas","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.com/tom131313/Example-LED","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"GitHub - tom131313/Example-LED","clicks":9}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":24594,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/how-do-you-program-pid/467993/5","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3402467,"name":"Tom Line","username":"Tom_Line","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/tom_line/{size}/236809_2.png","created_at":"2024-06-26T18:08:07.826Z","cooked":"<p>The wikipedia entry (surprisingly) has a great little chunk of pseudocode that I’ve had to restore a couple times when well wishers decided it was too straightforward.</p>
